ion and employment, the book argues that narratives are of fundamental importance for human cognition and identity construction. They help us understand the social and political world in which we live. The book emphasises the idea of intertextual narratability which holds that for narratives to become dominant they have to link themselves to previously existing stories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aInternational Relations 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aDiscourse analysis.  aInternational Relations.  aMercenaries.  aNarrative.  aPirates.  aPrivate military and security companies.  aRebels.  aRomanticism.1 aSpencer, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610024540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526100245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526100245/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles